What is your mywc program test plan?

Boundary tests:

mywc003.txt: This file contains only whitespace (spaces, tabs, and newlines), and so it checks the boundary case where there are characters and lines but zero words.

mywc004.txt: This file contains one word and no trailing newline, and so it checks the boundary case where EOF happens while still inside a word.

mywc002.txt: This file has a final line that does not end with '\n', and so it checks the boundary between line counting and character counting at end-of-file.

Statement tests:

mywc003.txt: This file contains only whitespace, and so causes the computer to execute lines 30-36, 42, 48-50, and 55-56 of the given mywc.c.

mywc001.txt: This file contains words separated by different amounts of spaces, and so causes the computer to execute lines 30-40, 42-50, and 55-56 of the given mywc.c.

mywc004.txt: This file contains one non-whitespace token with no trailing newline, and so causes the computer to execute lines 30-33, 34, 42-46, 52-53, and 55-56 of the given mywc.c.

mywc002.txt: This file contains words across two lines where the second line has no newline terminator, and so causes the computer to execute lines 30-50, 52-53, and 55-56 of the given mywc.c.

mywc005.txt: This file contains punctuation with mixed whitespace separators (including tabs), and so causes the computer to execute lines 30-50 and 55-56 of the given mywc.c while confirming punctuation is treated as part of words.

Stress tests:

mywc006.txt: This file contains very long words/lines, and so stress tests repeated character counting and memory-safe iteration over long input lines.

mywc007.txt: This file contains many repeated lines with many words per line, and so stress tests loop behavior over larger total input size and frequent word transitions.

